<!--Please see naming conventions at WP:MOSBIO, please do not add details like "Dr." (this includes adding degrees after name)-->'''Ronald Ernest Paul, Sr.''' (born [[August 20]], [[1935]]), is a ten-term [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[United States Congress|United States Congressman]] from [[Lake Jackson, Texas|Lake Jackson]], [[Texas]], a [[physician]], and a [[United States Republican presidential candidates, 2008|candidate]] for [[United States presidential election, 2008|U.S. president, 2008]]. He has represented [[Texas's 14th congressional district]] in the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] since 1997, and [[Texas's 22nd congressional district|its 22nd district]], 1976 – 1977 and 1979 – 1985. Paul also placed third in the [[United States presidential election, 1988|1988 presidential election]] as the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] nominee, while remaining a registered Republican. After graduation from [[Duke University School of Medicine]] and [[Residency (medicine)|residency]] in [[obstetrics]] and [[gynecology]] (ob/gyn), he was [[Conscription|drafted]] and served as a [[flight surgeon]] during, but not in, the [[Vietnam War]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Brockwell | first = I | date = 2007-07-15 | url = http://www.americanchronicle.com/articles/viewArticle.asp?articleID=32269 | title = Ron Paul – A True Patriot! | work = American Chronicle}}</ref>

Paul has been called "[[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]]",<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.memphisflyer.com/memphis/Content?oid=oid%3A31947 | work = Memphis Flyer | title = The "Ron Paul Revolution" | last = Baker | first = Jackson | date = 2007-08-09 | accessdate = 2007-09-27}}</ref> "[[Constitutionalism|Constitutionalist]]",<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.lewrockwell.com/orig5/galles6.html | title = The Constitutionalist | publisher = Lew Rockwell | last = Galles | first = Gary M | date = 2007-03-28 | accessdate = 2007-09-27}}</ref> and "[[libertarianism|libertarian]]".<ref>{{cite news | last = Snow | first = Nancy | date = 2006 | title = The Arrogance of American Power: What U.S. Leaders Are Doing Wrong and Why It's Our Duty to Dissent | publisher = Rowman & Littlefield | pages = 32}}</ref> He supports [[free trade]], [[Hard money (policy)|hard money]], sharply lower [[taxes]],<ref name="endirs">{{cite web | url = http://www.ronpaul2008.com/issues/end-the-irs/ | title = Ending the IRS | last = Paul | first = Ron | date = 2007-09 | accessdate = 2007-09-27 | publisher = Ron Paul 2008}}</ref> significantly [[Limited government|reduced government]], and [[non-interventionism|non-interventionist]] [[foreign policy]];<ref name="patriotism">{{cite news | title = Patriotism | url = http://www.lewrockwell.com/paul/paul388.html | work = Congressional Record | publisher = House of Representatives | last = Paul | first = Ron | date = 2007-05-22 | accessdate = 2007-09-27}}</ref> he voted against the [[Iraq War Resolution]] and the [[USA PATRIOT Act|Patriot Act]]. Paul states he has never voted in Congress to raise taxes or to approve an [[Deficit|unbalanced budget]];<ref name="2008bio">{{cite web | url = http://www.ronpaul2008.com/about/ | title = About Ron Paul | accessdate = 2007-09-27 | publisher = Ron Paul 2008}}</ref> he has called for the total abolition of the [[Internal Revenue Service]] (IRS) and the federal [[income tax]].<ref name="endirs"/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.antiwarpresident.com/ronpaul/Ron-Paul-less-government-abolish-IRS.html | title = Paul Want Less Government, Less Taxes, and Abolish IRS | publisher = Antiwar President | accessdate = 2007-09-27}}</ref> He also opposes [[Illegal immigration to the United States|illegal immigration]], [[gun control]], and the existence of many federal agencies. Paul ties his "strongly pro-life"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.house.gov/paul/congrec/congrec99/cr102799.htm | work = Congressional Record | publisher = House of Representatives | date = 1999-10-27 | accessdate = 2007-09-27 | title = PROVIDING FOR CONSIDERATION OF H.R. 2260, PAIN RELIEF PROMOTION ACT OF 1999}}</ref><ref name="teamliberty">{{cite news | url = http://www.teamliberty.net/id447.html | title = An Interview with Presidential Candidate Congressman Ron Paul | work = Muckraker Report | publisher = Team Liberty | last = Murtagh | first = Joseph | date = 2007-06-28 | accessdate = 2007-09-27}}</ref> views and his stance against federal death penalties<ref name="americanview">{{cite web | url = http://theamericanview.com/index.php?id=916&PHPSESSID=07e041c4300ca776c9ab8f30e1a35bbf | last = Lofton | first = John | title = Excerpts From Our Exclusive Ron Paul Interview | date = 2007-08 | accessdate = 2007-09-27 | publisher = American View}}</ref> to his advocacy of states' rights.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://ronpaulaudio.com/rpaudio/RonPaulRandiRhodesAirAmericainterview081607.m3u | publisher = Ron Paul Audio | work = Air America | date = 2007-08-16 | accessdate = 2007-09-27 | last = Rhodes | first = Randi | title = Ron Paul interview battles Air America Randi Rhodes Show}}</ref>

During his [[Ron Paul presidential campaign, 2008|2008 presidential campaign]], Paul has generated strong support on the [[Internet]]<ref name=usatweb>{{cite web | url = http://blogs.usatoday.com/onpolitics/2007/06/ron_pauls_web_o.html | title = Ron Paul's Web of support: He's an "online natural" | work = USA Today | date = 2007-06}}</ref> and is among the top Republican Internet search terms as measured by [[Hitwise]],<ref name=hitwise>{{cite web | url = http://www.hitwise.com/political-data-center/key-candidates-searchterms.php | title = Top 10 Presidential Candidate 2008 Search Terms | accessdate = 2007-08-15 | publisher = [[Hitwise]]}}</ref> [[Alexa Internet|Alexa]],<ref name=alexa>{{cite web | url = http://www.alexa.com/data/details/traffic_details?site0=ronpaul2008.com&site1=mittromney.com&site2=joinrudy2008.com&site3=JohnMcCain.com&site4=Fred2008.com&y=r&z=1&h=400&w=700&range=7d&size=Large&url=ronpaul2008.com | title = Alexa info for RonPaul2008.com, compared to other Republican candidates}}</ref> and [[Technorati]].<ref name="usnews0509">{{cite news | url = http://www.usnews.com/usnews/blogs/news_blog/070509/ron_pauls_online_rise.htm | work = U.S. News and World Report | title = Ron Paul's Online Rise | date = 2007-05-09 | accessdate = 2007-05-10}}</ref> At [[YouTube]], he leads the other presidential candidates, with over 29,000 subscribers.<ref name=youtube>{{cite web | url = http://www.techpresident.com/youtube | title = YouTube stats | publisher = Tech President}}</ref><ref name=ytc>{{cite web | url = http://www.youtube.com/profile?user=RonPaul2008dotcom | title = Ron Paul 2008 | publisher = YouTube | accessdate = 2007-09-27}}</ref> Supporters claim he is unfairly ignored by the media, and cite his victories in four out of five of the [[Republican presidential debates, 2008|2008 GOP debate]] sponsors' own online and phone text polls to argue he deserves more recognition.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.lewrockwell.com/woods/woods67.html | title = Defeat the Media Clones | publisher = Lew Rockwell | last = Woods, Jr. | first = Thomas E | date = 2007-05-10 | accessdate = 2007-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Wallenwein | first = A. | date = 2007-05-12 | url = http://www.opednews.com/articles/opedne_alex_wal_070512_media_blackout_boost.htm | title = Media Blackout Boosts Paul Campaign | publisher = Op-Ed News}}</ref> He places in the top tier in [[Straw polling for the 2008 United States presidential election|Republican straw polls]],<ref name="pollresults">http://www.ronpaul2008.com/straw-poll-results/</ref> but polls significantly lower among [[Gallup poll|Gallup]]<ref name=gallup92007>http://www.galluppoll.com/content/?ci=28702</ref> and Bloomberg<ref name="5nh">{{cite news | url = http://www.usaelectionpolls.com/2008/articles/ron-paul-now-at-five-percent-new-hampshire.html | last = Terr | first = David | publisher = USA Election Polls | title = Ron Paul Polling at 5% in New Hampshire | date = 2007-09-11 | accessdate = 2007-09-27}}</ref> phone samples of voters leaning Republican.

==Early life and education==

Paul was born in [[Green Tree, Pennsylvania|Green Tree]], [[Pennsylvania]], to Howard Caspar Paul, son of a [[Germany|German]] [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] [[immigrant]], and Margaret "Peggy" Dumont. His family owned a dairy farm in the small town, which lies just outside of [[Pittsburgh]].<ref name="dailypaul1">{{cite web | url = http://dailypaul.com/node/53 | title = The American Dream - Through the Eyes of Mrs. Ron Paul | last = Paul | first = Carol | date= 2007-03-16 | publisher= Daily Paul}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.wargs.com/political/paul.html | title = The Ancestors of Ron Paul | accessdate = 2007-05-20 | last = Reitwiesner | first = William Addams | publisher = Wargs}}</ref> He was the third of five sons born during seven years in the [[Great Depression]].<ref name="dailypaul1"/> Paul's father had an eighth-grade education and was co-owner, along with his siblings, Lewis and Arthur, of Green Tree Dairy. Paul began working at his father's dairy at age five. Later he delivered newspapers, worked in a drugstore, and became a [[milkman]] when he was old enough to drive.<ref name="dailypaul1"/> One of the customers on his milk route was baseball legend [[Honus Wagner]].<ref name="nytimesmagazine"/>

He graduated from Dormont High School in [[Dormont, Pennsylvania|Dormont]], [[Pennsylvania]], in 1953 with honors. He excelled in [[Athletics (track and field)|track and field]],<ref name="seattletimes">{{cite web | url = http://seattletimes.nwsource.com:80/html/nationworld/2003810874_paul29.html?syndication=rss | title = Profile: Republican Ron Paul | date = 2007-07-29 | work = Seattle Times}}</ref> winning the Pennsylvania state championship in the 220-yard dash and coming in second in the 440-yard dash as a junior. He also was on the [[wrestling]] team, played [[American football|football]] and [[baseball]], and was president of the student council.<ref name="nytimesmagazine"/><ref name="dailypaul1"/>

Paul paid for his first year at [[Gettysburg College]] with saved newspaper-delivery, lemonade-sale, and lawn-mowing money. Paul delivered mail and laundry on the side while in [[Gettysburg, Pennsylvania|Gettysburg]], [[Pennsylvania]]; for one year, he managed the college coffee shop.<ref name="dailypaul1"/> He gave up track after a knee injury but joined the college's [[swimming]] team instead after taking it up as therapy. He had been offered a full [[scholarship]] to run for the track team but declined it, concerned that he would not regain his previous speed.<ref name="dailypaul1"/> Paul was inducted into the [[Lambda Chi Alpha]] [[fraternity]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.fraternalcaucus.org/greeks_congress | title = Greeks in Congress | accessdate = 2007-07-08 | publisher = Capital Fraternal Caucus}}</ref> where he served as steward and house manager.<ref name="dailypaul1"/> He received his [[Bachelor of Arts]] [[Academic degree|degree]] in 1957.

Although he had once considered becoming a [[Lutheran]] minister like two of his brothers,<ref name="seattletimes"/> Paul decided to pursue a career in medicine instead and was accepted to [[Duke University School of Medicine]], where he received his [[Doctor of Medicine]] (M.D.) [[Academic degree|degree]] in 1961. He [[Internship|interned]] and began [[Residency (medicine)|residency]] training, both in [[internal medicine]], at [[Henry Ford Hospital]] in [[Detroit, Michigan|Detroit]], 1961 – 1962, and completed his residency in [[obstetrics|ob]]/[[gynecology|gyn]] at the [[University of Pittsburgh]], 1965 – 1968.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=P000583 | title = PAUL, Ronald Ernest | accessdate = 2007-05-20 | publisher = United States Congress}}</ref>

Paul adheres to the economic philosophy of the [[Austrian School]] of economics and has [[Ron Paul#Books authored|authored several books]] on the subject. He has pictures of [[classical liberal]] economists [[Friedrich Hayek]] and [[Ludwig von Mises]] hanging on his office wall.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.amconmag.com/2007/2007_06_18/cover.html | title = Lone Star | accessdate = 2007-09-27 | last = Dougherty | first = Michael Brendan | work = American Conservative | date = 2007-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://photos-184.ll.facebook.com/photos-ll-sf2p/v77/31/32/153800184/n153800184_30173281_6346.jpg | title = Screenshot | work = [[America: From Freedom to Fascism]]}}</ref>

==Family==

Paul married Carol Wells on [[February 1]], [[1957]]. Carol had asked Ron to their first date to a [[Sadie Hawkins dance]], and they kept in touch while attending colleges in different states. The couple married in Paul's senior year at [[Gettysburg College]]. While they lived in [[Detroit, Michigan|Detroit]] for his residency, Carol ran a dance school in their basement.<ref name="dailypaul1"/>

They have five children:<ref name="txmonthly2007">{{cite web | url = http://www.texasmonthly.com/preview/2007-08-01/feature2 | title = The Elephant in the Room | date = 2007-08 | work = [[Texas Monthly]]}}</ref> Ronnie, Lori, Rand, Robert, and Joy. They also have at least eighteen grandchildren and one great-grandchild.<ref name="seattletimes"/> Three of the Paul children, Robert, Rand, and Joy, also received M.D.'s:<ref name="txmonthly2007"/> Robert specializes in [[family practice]], Joy in [[obstetrics|ob]]/[[gynecology|gyn]] like her father, and Rand is an [[ophthalmology|eye surgeon]] in [[Bowling Green, Kentucky|Bowling Green]], [[Kentucky]], and founder of Kentucky Taxpayers United, who sometimes speaks at events as surrogate for his father.<ref name="firstfamily">{{cite web | url = http://www.dailypaul.com/node/185 | title = The First Family ??? | last = Pyeatt | first = Matt | date = 2007-05-24 | publisher = Daily Paul}}</ref><ref name="randpaul">{{cite web | url = http://www.ronpaul2008.com/events/rand-paul/ | title = Dr. Rand Paul: Upcoming Events | publisher= Ron Paul 2008}}</ref> Paul supported his children during their undergraduate and medical school years, not allowing them to take part in [[subsidy|subsidized]] federal [[student loan]] programs. He has not signed up for a [[Congressional pension]] for the same reason.<ref name="paulfacts">{{cite web | url = http://www.usnews.com/usnews/news/articles/070323/23paulfacts.htm | title = 10 Things You Didn't Know About Ron Paul | last = Burton | first = Danielle | date = 2007-03-23 | work = [[U.S. News & World Report]]}}</ref> Paul usually goes home to Lake Jackson on weekends.

When her husband was campaigning in the 14th district, Carol Paul decided to help his campaign by compiling family recipes into a cookbook and sending it to constituents.<ref name="txmonthly2007"/> The cookbook, now in its fifth edition, is filled with pictures of the large Paul family. Carol and the family keep a "Recipe of the Week" on her husband's Congressional campaign website.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://foodcompanycookbooks.blogspot.com/2007/05/ron-paul-family-cookbooks.html | title = Ron Paul Family Cookbooks | publisher = Food Company Cookbooks}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://ronpaulforcongress.com/html/carol.html | title = From the Desk of Carol Paul | publisher = Ron Paul for Congress}}</ref>

==Military service and medical career==

<!--Unsourced image removed: [[Image:Ron uniform.jpg|left|frame|Ron Paul while serving in the [[United States Air Force]].|{{deletable image-caption|1=Thursday, 27 September 2007}}]]-->

Paul's medical training was interrupted when he was [[Conscription in the United States|drafted]] into the [[United States Air Force]] during the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]]. He remained in the military during the early years of the [[Vietnam War]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://chbn.com/Clip.aspx?key=1CD9E3A0397BCBEC | title = Congressman Ron Paul Announces Presidential Run while taking LIVE calls on C-SPAN! | accessdate = 2007-07-08 | publisher = Capitol Hill Broadcasting Network | format = Flash video | quote = (11:26) I was drafted in the '60s. I went into the Air Force. I stayed in for five years in active duty and reserves.}}</ref> He served [[active duty]] as a [[flight surgeon]], 1963 – 1965, attending to the [[Otolaryngology|ear, nose, and throat]] problems of pilots in [[South Korea]], [[Iran]], [[Ethiopia]], and [[Turkey]], but was never sent to [[Vietnam]]. Based out of [[Kelly Air Force Base]] in [[San Antonio, Texas|San Antonio]], [[Texas]], Paul achieved the rank of [[Captain (army/air force)|captain]].<ref name="nytimesmagazine"/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.vote-smart.org/bio.php?can_id=BC031929 | title = Representative Ronald Ernest "Ron" Paul (TX) | publisher = Project Vote Smart}}</ref> He then served in the [[Air National Guard]], 1965 – 1968, while completing his [[Residency (medicine)|residency]] in [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ronpaulforcongress.com/html/veterans.html | title = Congressman Ron Paul – "Fighting For Our Country" | accessdate = 2007-07-08}}</ref>

Two years after leaving medical school, Paul worked in a church hospital's [[Emergency department|emergency room]] in [[San Antonio]] for a wage of [[US Dollar|$3]] per hour ($18 in [[Inflation|2007 dollars]]). Paul later specialized in [[obstetrics|ob]]/[[gynecology|gyn]] and eventually delivered more than 4,000 babies.<ref name="2008bio"/> Taking over the medical practice of a retiring doctor in [[Lake Jackson, Texas|Lake Jackson]], [[Texas]], he was busy as the only ob/gyn doctor in [[Brazoria County, Texas|Brazoria County]], saying, "I delivered forty to fifty babies a month and did a lot of surgery."<ref name="texasmonthly2001">{{cite web | url = http://www.texasmonthly.com/2001-10-01/feature7.php | title = Dr. No | last = Gwynne | first = S.C. | date = 2001-10-01 | work = [[Texas Monthly]]}}</ref> Paul refused [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] and [[Medicaid]] payments as a physician; instead, he worked [[Pro bono publico|for free]] or arranged discounted or custom-payment plans for needy patients.<ref name="paulfacts"/><ref name="paulsneary">{{cite web | url = http://calbears.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3827/is_199806/ai_n8799789 | title = Paul vs. Sneary | date = 1998-06-26 | accessdate = 2007-09-27 | work = Human Events}}</ref>

==Early Congressional career==

After several years as physician, Paul became a [[delegate]] to the 1974 Texas Republican [[Political convention|convention]]. He had decided to enter politics on [[August 15]], [[1971]], when [[President]] [[Richard Nixon]] advocated the U.S. dollar's complete departure from the [[gold standard]]. Paul said, "After that day, all money would be political money rather than money of real value. I was astounded."<ref name="texasmonthly2001"/>

[[Image:Ron Paul and Reagan.jpg|right|frame|Ron Paul led the Texas Delegation to nominate [[Ronald Reagan]] (left to right: Ron Paul, [[Jack Fields]], Ronald Reagan, and [[William Reynolds Archer, Jr.|Bill Archer]])]]

Paul was an unsuccessful Republican candidate for Congress from the 22nd district of Texas in 1974, against incumbent Democrat [[Robert R. Casey]], in an election where Democratic candidates won heavily. When [[President]] [[Gerald Ford]] appointed Casey as head of the [[Federal Maritime Commission]], Paul won an [[April]] [[1976]] [[special election]] to fill the empty seat. Paul lost six months later in the [[general election]], to Democrat [[Robert Gammage|Robert A. Gammage]], by fewer than 300 votes out of 180,000; he then defeated Gammage in a 1978 rematch and won new terms in 1980 and 1982. Paul was the first Republican representative from the area.<ref name="campaigncom">{{cite web | url = http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FgF-s1voM_Y | title = The Ron Paul Story | publisher = YouTube | accessdate = 2007-06-14}}</ref> He was also one of only four Republican Congressmen to endorse [[Ronald Reagan]] for president against [[Gerald Ford]] in 1976,<ref name="2008bio"/> when Paul led the Texas Reagan delegation at the national Republican convention.<ref name="campaigncom"/>

Paul delivered babies on Mondays and Saturdays during his entire term as the 22nd district representative.<ref name="texasmonthly2001"/> He began to gain his reputation as "Dr. No",<ref name="texasmonthly2001"/> with his refusal to vote for laws he felt to be unconstitutional.<ref name="campaigncom"/>

Paul was the first member of Congress, in the 1970's, to propose [[term limit]]s legislation in the House,<ref name="wsj1997">{{cite news | url = http://www.seedship.com/politics/ronpaul1.html | title = The Libertarian Congressman Is Back | work = Wall Street Journal | date = 1997-01-13 | page = A18 | accessdate = 2007-09-27}}</ref> where he also declined to attend junkets or register for a Congressional pension while serving four terms.<ref name="campaign1996">{{cite web | url = http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m2519/is_n6_v17/ai_18535311 | title = Paul vs. Laughlin – Ron Paul's campaign against Representative Greg Laughlin | last = Beiler | first = David | date = 1996-06 | publisher = Campaigns and Elections}}</ref> He proposed legislation to decrease Congressional pay by the rate of inflation.<ref name="wsj1997"/> In 1980, when a majority of Republicans favored [[President]] [[Jimmy Carter]]'s proposal to reinstate [[Selective Service|draft registration]], he pointed out the majority's views as inconsistent, stating they were more interested in registering their children than they were their guns.<ref name="wsj1997"/>

Paul served on the [[United States House Committee on Financial Services|House Banking Committee]], speaking against the inflation he saw as due to the [[Federal Reserve]],<ref name="2008bio"/> and against the deregulation of banking rules that allowed for the [[savings and loan crisis]] of the 1980's.<ref name="nytimesmagazine"/> The U.S. Gold Commission created by Congress in 1982 was his idea, and his conclusions from the commission were published by the [[Cato Institute]] as a book, ''The Case for Gold''.<ref name="gold">{{cite web | work = J. Taylor's Gold & Technology Stocks | date = 2000-05-11 | title = In Defense of our "Unalienable Rights" | url = http://www.usagold.com/gildedopinion/taylorpaulintrvw.html}}</ref> Paul's chief of staff from 1978 to 1982 was [[Lew Rockwell]].<ref name="insight1997">{{cite news | title = Insight on the News | date = 1997-01-10 | last= Berlau | first = John}}</ref> Paul was a regular participant in the annual Congressional [[baseball]] game.<ref name="campaigncom"/>

In 1984 Paul chose to run for the [[U.S. Senate]] instead of re-election to the House, but lost the [[Republican Party (United States)|GOP]] primary to [[Phil Gramm]].<ref name="nprpaulringo">{{cite news | title = National Public Radio | date = 2007-07-26 | last = Rudin | first = Ken}}</ref> He returned to full-time medical practice<ref name="2008bio"/> and was succeeded by [[Tom DeLay]], formerly a member of the [[Texas House of Representatives]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.lrl.state.tx.us/legis/members/roster.cfm?leg=68 | title = Members and leaders of the Texas Legislature | accessdate = 2007-07-08 | publisher = Legislative Reference Library of Texas}}</ref> In a farewell address on the House floor, Paul said, "Special interests have replaced the concern that the Founders had for general welfare. Vote trading is seen as good politics. The errand-boy mentality is ordinary, the defender of liberty is seen as bizarre. It's difficult for one who loves true liberty and utterly detests the power of the state to come to Washington for a period of time and not leave a true cynic."<ref name="insight1997"/>

==1988 presidential campaign==

In the [[United States presidential election, 1988|1988 presidential election]], Paul defeated American Indian activist [[Russell Means]] to win the [[United States Libertarian Party|Libertarian Party]] nomination for [[President of the United States|president]].<ref name="nytimesmagazine"/> Although he had been an early supporter of [[Ronald Reagan]], Paul was critical of the unprecedented [[deficits]] incurred by Reagan's administration, for which Paul's opponent [[George H.W. Bush]] had been [[Vice President of the United States|vice-president]].<ref name="campaign1996"/> On the ballot in 46 states and the [[District of Columbia]],<ref name="1988nytimes">{{cite web | url = http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0712FB3E5C0C748DDDA90994D0484D81 | title = Now for a Real Underdog: Ron Paul, Libertarian, for President | date = 1988-10-17 | work = [[New York Times]]}}</ref> he placed third in the [[popular vote]] with 431,750 votes (0.47%), behind Republican Bush and Democrat [[Michael Dukakis]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=940DEEDB103AF93AA15751C1A96E948260&n=Top%2fReference%2fTimes%20Topics%2fPeople%2fP%2fPaul%2c%20Ron | title = 1988 VOTE: The Final Word | date = 1988-12-29 | work = [[New York Times]]}}</ref> Paul was kept off the ballot in [[Missouri]] and received votes there only when [[write-in candidate|written-in]], reportedly due to a "technicality".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SL&p_theme=sl&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB3294736B1152B&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM | title = IF YOU DON'T LIKE BUSH OR DUKAKIS . . . LIBERTARIAN CANDIDATE OFFERS COMMON-SENSE POLICIES FOR AMERICA | date = 1988-11-07 | work = [[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]}}</ref>

During his candidacy, Paul was viewed as the Libertarian Party "standard bearer",<ref name="economist1988">{{cite news | title = The perils of punditry: The US election campaign | work = Economist | date = 1988-11-05 | url = http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-6898194.html | accessdate = 2007-09-11}}</ref><ref name="dallasmorningnews88">{{cite news | last = Attlesey | first = Sam | url = http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED3D00FAD249C49&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM | title = WARNING: POLITICAL CAMPAIGNS SET TO TACKLE TEXAS | work = [[Dallas Morning News]] | date = 1988-09-04 | accessdate = 2007-09-11 | quote = Republican presidential nominee George Bush, Democratic vice presidential hopeful Lloyd Bentsen, and Libertarian standard bearer Ron Paul ....}}</ref> gaining supporters nationwide who agreed with him on many positions — [[Second Amendment to the United States Constitution|gun rights]], [[fiscal conservatism]], [[home-schooling]], and [[pro-life|abortion]] — and winning approval from many who thought the federal government was heading in the wrong direction on other issues. These supporters formed a nationwide support base that encouraged him to return to office and supported his campaigns financially.<ref name="texasmonthly2001"/> His 2008 campaign chair, Kent Snyder, first worked for Paul on the 1988 campaign, when, Snyder says, Senator [[John McCain]] told him, "You're working for the most honest man in Congress."<ref name="txmonthly2007"/>

Paul said he sought to do more during his presidential run than reach office — he was spreading his liberty-minded ideas, often talking to groups of school and university students, whether or not they were old enough to vote: "We're just as interested in the future generation as this election. These kids will vote eventually, and maybe, just maybe, they'll go home and talk to their parents."<ref name="1988nytimes"/> He traveled the country for a year speaking about issues such as [[free market]] economics and the rising government deficits.<ref name="economist1988"/> He said, "That's why we talk to a lot of young people. They're the ones who are paying these bills, they're the ones who are inheriting this debt, so it's most likely these young people who will move into this next generation in government."<ref name="1988youtube">{{cite news | title = Interview with Ron Paul, 1988 | publisher = talk show | date = 1988 | url = http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=z4LSR8MvJnE&mode=related&search= | accessdate = 2007-09-17}}</ref>

After the election, Paul had a coin business,<ref name="spectator1999">{{cite news | title = A principled maverick | date = 1999-11 | work = American Spectator}}</ref> began his own [[think tank]], the Foundation for Rational Economics and Education, published an investment newsletter,<ref name="economist1988"/> and continued his medical practice until he returned to Congress.<ref name="nytimesmagazine"/><ref name="spectator1999"/>

==Newsletter article controversy==

A 1992 issue of the ''Ron Paul Survival Report'' (published by Paul since 1985) included derogatory comments concerning race and politicians.<ref>{{cite news | title = CAMPAIGN '96 U.S. HOUSE: Newsletter excerpts offer ammunition to Paul's opponent: GOP hopeful quoted on race, crime | url = http://web.archive.org/web/20070512114222/http://www.chron.com/content/chronicle/aol-metropolitan/96/05/23/paul.html | first = Alan | last = Bernstein | work = Houston Chronicle | date = 1996-05-22 | accessdate = 2007-05-20}}</ref> It accused [[President]] [[Bill Clinton]] of fathering [[Illegitimacy|illegitimate children]] and using [[cocaine]], and called [[U.S. House of Representatives|Representative]] [[Barbara Jordan]] a "fraud" and a "half-educated victimologist". The newsletter said government should lower the [[Defense of infancy|legal age for prosecuting youths as adults]], positing that some "black males age 13 ... are as big, strong, tough, scary and culpable as any adult" and that they can be "unbelievably fleet-footed" while committing crimes; it characterized 95% of [[Washington, D.C.]], black males as "semi-criminal or entirely criminal" and only 5% of blacks as "sensible". It also held that "complex embezzling" was a "100 percent white and Asian" crime and called Israelis a lobby "of the bad sort".<ref>{{cite news | last = Searcy | first = R | date = 2007-06-03 | url = http://www.atlantaprogressivenews.com/views/0024-views.html | title = The Ron Paul that Ron Paul Doesn't Want You to Know | work = Atlanta Progressive News}}</ref>

In 2001, Paul took "moral responsibility for" the comments printed in his newsletter under his name, explaining they were written by a [[ghostwriter|guest writer]] and did not represent his views. He said the remarks referring to Rep. Jordan were "the saddest thing, because Barbara and I served together and actually she was a delightful lady."<ref name="texasmonthly2001"/><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.freemarketnews.com/WorldNews.asp?nid=41822 | title = Ron Paul Race Smear Erased? | date = 2007-05-22 | work = Free Market News | publisher = Free Market News Network}}</ref> ''Texas Monthly'' magazine defended Paul's decision to protect the writer's confidence during previous campaigns, concluding, "Even more puzzling was that, in four terms as a U.S. congressman and one presidential race, Paul had never uttered anything remotely like this."<ref name="texasmonthly2001"/>

==Later Congressional career==

===Campaigns===

[[Image:Ron paul.jpg|right|200px|thumb|Paul's Congressional portrait]]

In 1996, Paul returned to Congress after a tougher battle than he had faced in the 1970's. He was hopeful of being more effective in Congress after the Republicans took over both houses of Congress in the [[United States House elections, 1994|1994 election]].<ref name="paulsneary"/> His primary opponent, [[Greg Laughlin]], had support from Republican leaders, including House Speaker [[Newt Gingrich]] and Texas Governor [[George W. Bush]].<ref name="campaign1996"/> Incumbent Laughlin had switched from the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] to the Republican side the year before, and the [[Republican National Committee]], hoping to encourage other Democrats to switch parties, threw its full support behind Laughlin. Despite these efforts by the national party, the [[NRA|National Rifle Association]], and other interest groups, challenger Paul won the primary. It became the third time he had been elected to Congress as a non-incumbent.<ref name="nytimesmagazine"/>

While Gingrich and other Republican leaders visited the district stumping for Laughlin, Paul ran newspaper ads quoting Gingrich's harsh criticisms of Laughlin's voting record 14 months earlier, before Laughlin had switched parties.<ref name="campaign1996"/> Baseball pitcher (and constituent) [[Nolan Ryan]], a friend of Paul's, served as his honorary campaign chair and appeared in ads for him, and tax activist [[Steve Forbes]] also supported Paul's candidacy.<ref name="nytimesmagazine"/><ref name="texasmonthly2001"/> Paul continued to maintain his home in Lake Jackson, but ran for the coastal 14th Congressional district rather than the 22nd district he had previously represented, due to redistricting borders.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://ao.nictusa.com/ao/no/900023.html | title = Federal Election Commission Advisory Opinion Number 1990-23 | accessdate = 2007-05-26 | last = Elliott | first = Lee Ann | date= 1990-11-05 | publisher= Federal Election Commission}}</ref>

His Democratic opponent in the fall election, trial [[lawyer]] Charles "Lefty" Morris, lost in a close margin, despite assistance from the [[AFL-CIO|American Federation of Labor]] and running numerous attacks citing Paul's 1992 newsletter and his past votes to repeal federal [[Prohibition (drugs)|drug laws]] in favor of state legislation. Paul in turn labeled Morris a pawn of trial lawyers and big labor, and raised more money than Morris, with the help of his national network of donors: $1.2 million to Morris's less than $0.5 million. Ken Bryan, a Democratic consultant to some of Paul's opponents, has said, "He has one of the largest contributor bases in Congress, outside of the leadership." Most of Paul's contributions are given in small amounts by individuals.<ref name="texasmonthly2001"/> That year, he had the third-highest amount of individual contributions of any House member, behind Gingrich and [[Bob Dornan]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.reason.com/news/show/118086.html | title = Paul for President?: The maverick libertarian Republican talks on war, immigration, and presidential ambition | accessdate = 2007-05-28 | last = Doherty | first = Brian | date = 2007-01-22 | work = Reason}}</ref>

In 1998 Paul again won the primary and the election, outraising his opponent by a large margin, $2.1 million to $0.7 million. Opposing a Democratic rice farmer and former [[Matagorda County, Texas|Matagorda County]] judge, Loy Sneary, Paul won by 11%; he ran ads warning voters to be "leery of Sneary".<ref name="saynot">{{cite web | url = http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/07/08/AR2006070800966_2.html | title = Congressman Paul's Legislative Strategy? He'd Rather Say Not | last = Copeland | first = Libby | date = 2006-07-09 | work = [[Washington Post]]}}</ref> Paul accused Judge Sneary of voting to raise his pay by 5%, increasing his judge's travel budget by 400% in one year, and creating more government bureaucracy by starting a new government agency to handle a [[license plate]] fee he enacted. Sneary's aides said he had voted to raise all county employees' pay by 5% in a "cost of living" increase. Paul countered that he had never voted to raise Congressional pay.<ref name="paulsneary"/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.chron.com/cgi-bin/auth/story.mpl/content/chronicle/metropolitan/98/08/15/notebook.2-0.html | title = Foes lock horns over Paul's radio ads | accessdate = 2007-05-26 | date = 1998-08-14 | work = Campaign Notebook | publisher = Houston Chronicle}}</ref>

In 2000, Sneary ran against Paul again, with Paul winning 60% to 40% and raising $2.4 million to Sneary's $1.1 million.<ref name="texasmonthly2001"/> Paul was re-elected in 2002, in 2004 (unopposed), and in 2006 to his tenth term (by 20%),<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2006//pages/results/states/TX/index.html | title = State Races: Texas | accessdate = 2007-03-04 | work = Elections 2006 | publisher= Cable News Network}}</ref> outraising his opponent $1.2 million to $0.6 million.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.thevictoriaadvocate.com/330/story/72352.html | title = Shane Sklar won't run against Paul in 2008 | accessdate = 2007-06-14 | work = Elections 2008 | publisher = Victoria Advocate}}</ref> He has drawn two primary challengers in the 2008 election: Eric Dondero, a former aide fired by Paul,<ref name="nytimesmagazine"/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://reason.com/blog/show/120230.html | title = Blowback, Texas-Style | accessdate= 2007-07-11 | work= Reason}}</ref> and Chris Peden, a [[Friendswood, Texas|Friendswood]] city councilman.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/politics/stories/MYSA052207.EN.PAUL.94898f61.html | title = Paul gets primary challenger | accessdate = 2007-07-11 | work = San Antonio Express-News}}</ref>

===Relationship with district===

Paul continued to work as an [[obstetrician]] in [[Brazoria County, Texas|Brazoria County]], [[Texas]], even while serving in [[United States Congress|Congress]], delivering many of his constituents' babies. As of 2001, he was one of few doctors in the House (eight, including dentists) and part of an even smaller group that continued to practice while in office. Journalists have reported that it is not unusual for younger people in his home district to approach the Congressman and say that he delivered them.<ref name="texasmonthly2001"/>

Paul opposes some forms of legislation that coastal or rural members of Congress typically support. Paul's district in Texas is larger in size than [[Massachusetts]],<ref name="washpost96">{{cite news | title = GOP House Candidate Responds to Charges | accessdate = 2007-09-11 | last = Pressley | first = Sue Ann | date = 1996-05-26 | work = Washington Post}}</ref> borders the [[Gulf of Mexico]] with 675 miles (1100 kilometers) of coastline, and also includes suburbs of [[Houston]]; it was [[2003 Texas redistricting|redistricted]] prior to the 2004 election. Paul is opposed to federally funded [[flood insurance]] because it requires those who do not live near [[flood]] zones to subsidize those who choose to live in an area that is prone to flooding, and does not allow those in flood zones to choose their own insurer. In an "overwhelmingly rural region", Paul opposes farm subsidies because they go to big corporations rather than small farmers. Despite voting against bills with large support in Congress, such as the farm bill, the Congressman's "contrarian nature" and devotion to lowering taxes has continuously appealed to 14th district voters.<ref name="texasmonthly2001"/> One survey conducted by Paul of the constituency found that 54% agreed with his goal of eliminating the federal [[United States Department of Education|Department of Education]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.house.gov/paul/tst/tst97/tst072097.htm | title = Parents must have control of education | accessdate = 2007-09-13 | last = Paul | first = Ron | date = 1997-07-20 | work = Texas Straight Talk | publisher = House of Representatives}}</ref>

While Paul votes against most spending bills, he has diverted funds that have already been authorized by other bills into his own district.<ref name="wsj2003">{{cite web | url = http://online.wsj.com/article_email/SB104725224693862700.html | title = A Far-Right Texan Inspires Antiwar Left | accessdate = 2007-06-15 | last = Murray | first = Shailagh | date = 2003-03-10 | work = Wall Street Journal}}</ref> Paul spends extra time in the district addressing constituents' concerns, to compensate for "violat[ing] almost every rule of political survival you can think of",<ref name="texasmonthly2001"/> sometimes three to four days a week, often accompanied by grandchildren. He attends graduations, civic ceremonies, and [[Boy Scouts of America|Boy Scout]] honor ceremonies. In an expansive district, he often logs over 300 miles (500 kilometers) daily, visiting [[constituents]] or handling their concerns. He reaches out to 14th district voters on veterans' issues, such as procuring medals for war veterans who lost or never received their medals, and holding medal ceremonies for those whose medals are being presented. He has helped senior citizens of the district get free or low-cost prescription drugs through a little-known drug company program; his staff sends out birthday cards to constituents, as well as [[condolence]] cards on the deaths of family members.<ref name="texasmonthly2001"/>

===Legislation===

Paul sponsors many more bills than the average representative, such as those that would abolish the [[income tax]]<ref name="endirs"/> or the [[Federal Reserve]]; many do not escape committee review. Nevertheless, he has been named one of the "50 Most Effective Members of Congress" by ''Congressional Quarterly''.<ref name="ronpaulis">{{cite web | url = http://www.ronpaulforcongress.com/html/ronpaulis.html | title = Ron Paul Is… | accessdate = 2007-06-15 | publisher = Ron Paul for Congress}}</ref> He has sponsored successful legislation to prevent the [[Department of Housing and Urban Development]] from seizing a church in New York through [[eminent domain]], and a bill transferring ownership of the [[Lake Texana]] dam project from the federal government to [[Texas]].<ref name="texasmonthly2001"/>

Paul has introduced bills that would apply a $5,000 tax credit per child towards spending on any type of children's education–related expenses, [[public education|public]], [[Private education#North America|private]], or [[Homeschooling|homeschool]]. He has introduced the [[Family Education Freedom Act]] in every Congressional session since 1997; the bill currently has six co-sponsors.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hslda.org/legislation/national/2001/HR368/default.asp | title = H.R. 368 – Family Education Freedom Act of 2001 | accessdate = 2007-09-13 | date = 2002-06-27 | publisher = Home School Legal Defense Assocation}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.washingtonwatch.com/bills/show/110_HR_1056.html | title = H.R. 1056, The Family Education Freedom Act of 2007 | accessdate = 2007-09-13 | publisher = Washington Watch}}</ref> He has also introduced companion legislation in the form of the [[Teacher Tax Cut Act]], which would provide all elementary and secondary school teachers with a $1,000 tax cut, and the Professional Educators Tax Relief Act, which would give all K-12 school librarians, counselors, and other personnel the same $1,000 tax credit.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.house.gov/paul/congrec/congrec2003/cr021103d.htm | title = Teacher Tax Cut Act | accessdate = 2007-09-14 | publisher = House of Representatives | work = Congressional Record}}</ref> He has also introduced the [[Education Improvement Tax Cut Act]], which would allow $5,000 deductions for any type of donations to scholarships or to benefit academics at any school.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.educationpolicy.org/newsletter/EEMar99.htm | title = Rep. Paul Introduces Education Package | accessdate = 2007-09-14 | date = 1999-03 | work= Education Exchange | publisher = Education Policy}}</ref>

In [[March 2001]], Paul introduced the "Constitutional War Powers Resolution of 2001", which would repeal the 1973 [[War Powers Resolution]] (WPR) and thus prohibit presidents from initiating a war without a formal [[Declaration of war by the United States|declaration of war by Congress]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.worldnetdaily.com/news/article.asp?ARTICLE_ID=22022 | title = Bill would restore Congress' war powers | accessdate = 2007-06-13 | first = Jon | last= Dougherty | date = 2001-03-13 | work = WorldNetDaily}}</ref> Later in 2001, however, Paul voted for the [[Authorization for Use of Military Force]], which authorized the president, pursuant to WPR, to respond to those responsible for the [[2001]] [[World Trade Center]] terror attack.<ref name="AUMF">{{cite web | title = Key Vote (How all members voted) Authorization for Use of Military Force | url = http://www.vote-smart.org/issue_keyvote_member.php?cs_id=V3064 | publisher = Project Vote Smart | accessdate = 2007-07-16}}</ref> In order to prevent Congress from yielding its Constitutional authority to declare war to the executive branch, which does not Constitutionally hold that power, Paul introduced legislation in [[October 2002]] giving Congress the opportunity to declare war on [[Iraq]], rather than merely "authorizing" the president to deploy forces without a declaration of war. He said he would not vote for his own bill, but if his fellow members of Congress wished to go to war in Iraq, they should follow the Constitution and declare war. As one of six Republicans to vote against the Iraq War Resolution, Paul inspired the founding of a group called the National Peace Lobby Project to promote a resolution he and Oregon representative [[Peter DeFazio]] sponsored to repeal the war authorization in February 2003. His speech, 35 "Questions That Won't Be Asked About Iraq",<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.house.gov/paul/congrec/congrec2002/cr091002.htm | title = Questions That Won't Be Asked About Iraq | accessdate = 2007-07-12 | first = Ron | last = Paul | date = 2002-09-10 | publisher= House of Representatives | work = Congressional Record}}</ref> was translated and published in German, French, Russian, Italian, and Swiss publications before the Iraq War began.<ref name="wsj2003"/>

Paul says his fellow members of Congress have increased government spending by 75 percent during [[George W. Bush]]'s administration.<ref name="endirs"/> After a 2005 bill was touted as "slashing" government waste, Paul wrote that it decreased spending by a fraction of one percent and that "Congress couldn't slash spending if the members' lives depended on it."<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.lewrockwell.com/paul/paul287.html | title = Too Little Too Late | accessdate = 2007-06-13 | first = Ron | last = Paul | date = 2005-11-15 | publisher = Lew Rockwell}}</ref> Paul said that between 2001 and early 2004 he had voted against more than 700 bills intended to expand government.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.lewrockwell.com/yates/yates92.html | title = An Evening With Dr. Ron Paul | accessdate = 2007-09-27 | first = Steven | last = Yates, Ph.D. | date = 2004-04-07 | publisher = Lew Rockwell}}</ref>

Paul charged his fellow legislators with voting for the Patriot Act without reading it first; more than 300 pages long, it was enacted into law less than 24 hours after being introduced. In response to such Congressional actions, Paul introduced "Sunlight Rule" legislation, which would not allow votes on legislation to occur until ten days after its introduction, with the intent of giving lawmakers enough time to read bills before voting on them. The bill requires allotting 72 hours for House members and staff to examine the contents of amendments.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.house.gov/paul/tst/tst2007/tst091607.htm | title = The Sunlight Rule | accessdate = 2007-09-27 | first = Ron | last = Paul | date = 2007-09-16 | publisher = House of Representatives | work = Texas Straight Talk}}</ref>

In 2005 and 2007, Paul introduced the Sanctity of Life Act, which would provide that human life exists from conception, removing abortion from federal jurisdiction and effectively negating [[''Roe v. Wade'']].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.govtrack.us/congress/billtext.xpd?bill=h109-776 | title = H.R. 776 of the 109th Congress, "Sanctity of Life Act of 2005"}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c110:H.R.1094.IH: | title = Sanctity of Life Act of 2007 | publisher = Thomas}}</ref> Paul has also introduced a Constitutional amendment with similar intent. Such laws would permit states to declare abortion to be murder and to outlaw new fetal stem cell research and some contraception and fertility treatments.<ref>{{cite news | last = Sealover | first = E | date = 2007-07-16 | url = http://www.gazette.com/articles/abortion_24888___article.html/colorado_group.html | title = Ballot initiative would outlaw abortion | work = Colorado Springs Gazette}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Stevens | first = A | date = 2007-06-10 | url = http://www.connectsavannah.com/gyrobase/Content?oid=oid%3A313 | title = 'Missing angels' or misogyny? | work = Women's eNews | publisher = Connect Savannah}}</ref> Also in 2005 and 2007, Paul introduced the We the People Act, which would forbid all federal courts from adjudicating abortion as well as same-sex marriage, sexual practices, and government display of religious symbols. The Act would make federal decisions on those subjects nonbinding as state precedent, and would forbid federal courts from spending money to enforce their judgments.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.govtrack.us/congress/billtext.xpd?bill=h109-4379 | title = H.R. 4379 of the 109th Congress, "We the People Act" | publisher = House of Representatives}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c110:H.R.300: | title = We the People Act of 2007 | publisher = Thomas}}</ref>

===Affiliations===

Paul serves on the House [[United States House Committee on International Relations|International Relations Committee]] (having been on the Western Hemisphere and the Asia and Pacific subcommittees); the Joint Economic Committee; and the [[United States House Committee on Financial Services|Committee on Financial Services]] (as Ranking Member of the Domestic and International Monetary Policy, Trade and Technology subcommittee, and Vice-Chair of the Oversight and Investigations subcommittee).<ref name="officialbio">{{cite web | url = http://www.house.gov/paul/bio.shtml | title = Who is Ron Paul? | accessdate = 2007-09-27 | publisher = House of Representatives}}</ref>

Paul served as honorary chair of, and is a current member of, the [[Republican Liberty Caucus]], a political action organization dedicated to promoting the ideals of individual rights, limited government and free enterprise within the Republican Party.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://fl.rlc.org/ | title = RLC of Florida | accessdate = 2007-03-04 | publisher = Republican Liberty Caucus of Florida}}</ref> He also serves on the Liberty Caucus (or Liberty Committee), a group of liberty-minded representatives from both sides of the aisle,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.thelibertycommittee.org/ | title = The Liberty Committee | accessdate = 2007-06-24}}</ref> hosting a luncheon for the Liberty Caucus every Thursday. Other members include [[Walter B. Jones]] of [[North Carolina]], [[Jimmy Duncan (U.S. politician)|Jimmy Duncan]] and [[Zach Wamp]] of [[Tennessee]], [[Virgil Goode]] of [[Virginia]], [[Roscoe Bartlett]] of [[Maryland]], [[Scott Garrett]] of [[New Jersey]], and [[Jeff Flake]] of [[Arizona]].<ref name="nytimesmagazine"/> Paul is a founding member of the Congressional Rural Caucus, which deals with agricultural and rural issues,<ref name="ronpaulis"/> and the [[Congressional Wildlife Refuge Caucus]].

Unlike many political candidates, Paul receives the overwhelming majority of his campaign contributions from individuals.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.asp?CID=N00005906&cycle=2006 | work = Contributions | accessdate = 2007-05-25 | title = Ron Paul: Campaign Finance/Money | publisher = Open Secrets}}</ref> In 2005 – 2006, individuals contributed 96.8% of the funds he raised. Federal Election Commission records show Paul accepts money from [[Political_Action_Committee|political action committees]] (PAC's), although much less than most of his counterparts in Congress. Paul received PAC money during the 1998 (5.7%), 2000 (4.5%), 2002 (1.8%), 2004 (5.8%), and 2006 (2.1%) Congressional electoral cycles.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.opensecrets.org/pacs/memberprofile.asp?cid=N00005906&Cycle=2006&CollapseAll=TRUE | title= PAC Contributions to Paul, Ron (R-TX) | accessdate = 2007-06-04 | publisher = Open Secrets}}</ref> In a special report, the group Clean Up Washington listed Paul as taking the seventh-lowest amount of PAC money of all House members, as well as accepting one of the lowest amounts of lobbyist money and taking the fourth-highest percentage of contributions from small donors. Their data studied contributions from the 2000 election cycle to midway through 2006.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.cleanupwashington.org/sii/pdfs/factsheet.pdf | title = Under the Influence: Highlights from Public Citizen's Special Interest Index | accessdate = 2007-06-04 | date = 2006-10 | publisher = [[Public Citizen]]}}</ref> Of the 2008 Republican presidential candidates, he has accepted the lowest percentage of PAC money.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.opensecrets.org/pres08/summary.asp?id=N00005906&cycle=2008 | title = 2008 Presidential Election: Ron Paul Campaign Money | accessdate = 2007-06-04 | publisher = Open Secrets}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.opensecrets.org/pres08/index.asp | title = 2008 Presidential Election: Banking on Becoming President | accessdate = 2007-06-04 | publisher = Open Secrets}}</ref>

Paul remains on good terms with the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]]: he addressed its 2004 [[Libertarian National Convention|national convention]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.theadvocates.org/liberator/vol-09-num-10.htm | title = President's Corner | accessdate = 2007-05-28 | date = 2004-06-09 | work = Liberator Online, 9:10 | publisher = Advocates for Self-Government}}</ref> He also was endorsed by the Constitution Party's 2004 presidential candidate, [[Michael Peroutka]]. Paul is a potential nominee of both parties independently of the [[Republican National Convention]]'s nomination.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://freemarketnews.com/WorldNews.asp?nid=49495 | title = Ron Paul Triple Nomination Threat? | author = Staff Selections | work = Free Market News | publisher = Free Market News Network | date = 2007-09-26 | accessdate = 2007-09-27}}</ref>

===Actions in Congress===

Paul was on a bipartisan coalition of 17 members of Congress that sued [[President]] [[Bill Clinton|Clinton]] in 1999 over his conduct of the [[Kosovo]] war. They accused Clinton of failing to inform Congress of the action's status within 48 hours as required by [[War Powers Resolution|WPR]], and of failing to obtain Congressional declaration of war as specifically required in the Constitution. Congress had voted 427 – 2 against a declaration of war with [[Yugoslavia]], and had voted to deny support for the air campaign in Kosovo. A federal judge dismissed the lawsuit, ruling that since Congress had voted for funding after Clinton had actively engaged troops in the war with Kosovo, legislators had sent a confusing message about whether they approved of the war. Paul said that the judge's decision attempted to circumvent the Constitution and to authorize the president to conduct a war without approval from Congress.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.house.gov/paul/press/press99/pr060999.htm | title = Judge sides with Clinton | accessdate = 2007-06-12 | first = Ron | last = Paul | date = 1999-06-09 | publisher = House of Representatives}}</ref>

==2008 presidential campaign==

<!-- READ THIS FIRST: Only add major developments and events to this section, keeping the section brief. All other material should be contributed to [[Ron Paul presidential campaign, 2008]]. Avoid giving undue mention of third parties commenting on Paul's campaign (polls, blogs, etc.) rather than facts about the campaign itself. -->

{{Future election candidate|Paul, Ron}}

[[Image:RonPaul2008.png|300px|thumb|right|Ron Paul's campaign slogan, "Hope for America"]]

{{main|Ron Paul presidential campaign, 2008}}

On [[February 19]], [[2007]], Paul formed an [[exploratory committee]] to gauge support for a run in the [[United States presidential election, 2008|2008 U.S. presidential election]].<ref name="CSPAN">{{cite web | url = http://chbn.com/Clip.aspx?key=1CD9E3A0397BCBEC | title = Congressman Ron Paul Announces Presidential Run while taking LIVE calls on C-SPAN! | accessdate = 2007-07-08 | publisher = Capital Hill Broadcasting Network | format = Flash video}}</ref> Saying he was "pleasantly surprised" by the committee's findings, Paul formally declared his candidacy for the [[Republican Party (United States) presidential primaries, 2008|Republican nomination]] on [[March 12]], [[2007]], as a guest on [[C-SPAN]]'s ''[[Washington Journal]]''.<ref name="CSPAN"/><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.mysanantonio.com/news/metro/stories/MYSA031207.paul2008.EN.74141d9.html | title = Paul formally launches presidential bid | first = Gary | last = Martin | work = San Antonio Express-News | date = 2007-03-12 | accessdate = 2007-03-13}}</ref> Prior to his campaign, in a [[February 2007]] [[CNN]] [[Opinion poll#Coverage bias|telephone poll]], Paul was the candidate with the least name recognition besides [[John H. Cox]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.usaelectionpolls.com/2008/articles/ron-paul-unknown-in-new-hampshire.html | title = CNN/WMUR Granite State Poll, New Hampshire Primary Poll (February 2007) | accessdate = 2007-06-08 | date = 2007-05-18 | publisher = USA Election Polls}}</ref>

===Campaign finances===

By May 2007, Paul had come in second in fundraising in [[Montana]] and at the head of the pack of then–second-tier candidates in 14 other states.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,273302,00.html | title = Texas Congressman Ron Paul Hopes to Garner Support for Presidential Bid with Internet, Debates | author = Associated Press | date = 2007-05-17 | publisher = Fox News}}</ref> As of [[July 6]], Ron Paul had the third most cash on hand of the Republican candidates with $2.4 million, putting him ahead of [[John McCain]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalradar/2007/07/ron-paul-tops-m.html | title = Ron Paul Tops McCain in Cash on Hand | accessdate = 2007-07-07 | publisher= ABC News | date = 2007-07-06}}</ref> Over 99% of Paul's funds had come from individuals,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.opensecrets.org/pres08/summary.asp?id=N00005906&cycle=2008 | title = Ron Paul Campaign Money | accessdate = 2007-08-06 | publisher = Open Secrets}}</ref> with almost half (47%) raised from small contributions ($200 or less).<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.cfinst.org/pr/prRelease.aspx?ReleaseID=155 | title = The Presidential Campaigns Are Setting Records | work = CFI Analysis of FEC Reports through [[June 30]] | publisher = Campaign Finance Institute}}</ref>

[[Federal Election Commission]] finance reports for second quarter 2007 indicate that Ron Paul had topped all other presidential candidates in campaign contributions from employees of the armed services, receiving 26.2% of military donations.<ref>{{cite news | last = Englehardt | first = T | date = 2007-07-23 | url = http://www.thenation.com/doc/20070730/engelhardt | title = Why the US Military Loves Ron Paul | work = Nation}}</ref> Among Republican contenders Paul had 49.5% of military support, or nearly as much as all others combined.<ref>{{cite news | http://query.nictusa.com/pres/2007/Q2/ | title = Selected Presidential Reports For The 2007 July Quarterly | publisher = [[Federal Election Commission]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://thespinfactor.com/thetruth/2007/07/16/military-support-for-the-republican-candidates/ | title = Military support for the republican candidates | work = Spin Factor | date = 2007-07-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://thespinfactor.com/thetruth/2007/07/17/ron-paul-leads-all-08-candidates-with-one-third-of-military-contributions-for-q2/ | title = Ron Paul leads ALL '08 candidates with over one-fourth of military contributions for Q2 | work = Spin Factor | date = 2007-07-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://ronpauldelaware.wordpress.com/2007/07/16/military-favors-ron-paul-over-mccain/ | title = Military Favors Ron Paul Over McCain | work = Delaware Ron Paul | date = 2007-07-16}}</ref>

Fundraising strengthened again in third quarter 2007, with an August competition among Paul's over 700 local volunteer [[Meetup.com|meetup]] groups<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ronpaul2008.com/meetup | date = 2007-08 | accessdate = 2007-09-27 | title = Meetup Competition | publisher = Ron Paul 2008 | last = Bydlak | first = Jonathan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://ronpaul2008.typepad.com/ron_paul_2008/2007/08/meetup-competit.html | date = 2007-08-23 | accessdate = 2007-09-27 | title = Meetup Competition Update | publisher = Ron Paul 2008 | last = Bydlak | first = Jonathan}}</ref> and a fundraising drive the last week of September with a goal of raising $500,000 online by [[September 30]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://thehill.com/campaign-2008/pay-pals--paul-supporters-reach-into-their-pockets-2007-09-25.html | title = Pay Pals – Paul supporters reach into their pockets | last = Marre | first = Klaus | date = 2007-09-25 | accessdate = 2007-09-27 | work = The Hill: Campaign 2008}}</ref> When the initial goal was well-surpassed after only three days, Paul raised the goal to $1 million, telling supporters, "Frankly, I'm floored. And very, very grateful."<ref>{{cite web | last = Paul | first = Ron | url = http://ronpaul2008.typepad.com/ron_paul_2008/2007/09/message-from--3.html | title = Message from Ron Paul: Let's Do It! | date = 2007-09-27 | accessdate = 2007-09-27}}</ref> This new goal of $1 million was met during the evening of [[September 29]].<ref>{{cite web | last = Paul | first = Ron | url = http://www.ronpaul2008.com/ | title = Ron Paul 2008 | date = 2007-09-29 | accessdate = 2007-09-29}}</ref>

===Polling===

{{main|Opinion polling for the Republican Party (United States) 2008 presidential candidates}}

{{main|Straw polling for the 2008 United States presidential election}}

In a [[Zogby]] phone poll released on [[May 17]], Paul drew 3% of the respondents determined as "likely New Hampshire Republican primary voters", fifth place among Republican contenders.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.zogby.com/news/ReadNews.dbm?ID=1302 | title = Zogby: Romney Widens Lead in New Hampshire | accessdate = 2007-06-08 | date = 2007-05-17 | publisher = Zogby International}}</ref> By September, Paul's support in this early-primary state had risen to 5%, according to a Bloomberg poll.<ref name="5nh"/> In the same month [[Gallup]] polled Paul at 4% nationwide among likely Republican voters.<ref name="gallup92007"/>

Paul's support at local-event–based [[Straw polling for the 2008 United States presidential election|Republican straw polls]] consistently outstrips his phone poll performances. At the Utah GOP convention on [[June 9]], [[2007]], Paul placed second behind [[Mitt Romney]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.freedomsphoenix.com/Feature-Article.htm?InfoNo=019804 | title = Utah State Republican Convention Straw Poll Results | last = Gammill | first = Powell | date = 2007-06-08 | publisher = Freedom's Phoenix | accessdate = 2007-09-27}}</ref> On [[July 28]], Paul received 18% and placed second only to then-undeclared candidate [[Fred Thompson]] in a [[Georgetown County]], [[South Carolina]], Republican Party straw poll.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://georgetowngop.blogspot.com/2007/07/fred-thompson-wins-georgetown-county.html | title = Fred Thompson Wins Georgetown County Straw Poll | last = Swatzel | first = Tom |  publisher = Georgetown County Republican Party | date = 2007-07-28 | accessdate = 2007-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://ronpaul2008.typepad.com/ron_paul_2008/2007/07/ron-paul-beats-.html | title = Paul Beats Romney, Giuliani and McCain | date = 2007-07-28 | publisher = Ron Paul 2008 | accessdate = 2007-09-27}}</ref> In the larger [[Ames Straw Poll|Iowa straw poll]] on [[August 11]], Paul received 9% and fifth place.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.iowagop.net/shownews.asp?artid=20 | title = Mitt Romney Wins Iowa Straw Poll | last = Tiffany | first = Mary | date = 2007-08-12 | accesdate = 2007-09-27 | publisher = Republican Party of Iowa}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Glover | first = M | date = 2007-08-11 | url = http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2007/08/11/ap4011007.html | title = Romney Wins Iowa Straw Poll As Expected | author = Associated Press | work = Forbes}}</ref> In the [[Springfield, Illinois|Springfield]], [[Illinois]], Republican Straw Poll of [[August 16]], Ron Paul won 19% of the vote, third behind Romney and Thompson.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://weareillinois.org/Connect/Detail/tabid/73/news_item_id/345/Default.aspx | title = Mitt Romney Wins Illinois Straw Poll | accessdate = 2007-09-17 | publisher = Illinois Republican Party | date = 2007-08-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/chi-straw_poll_web_aug17,0,2733296.story | title = Vote not much to crow about | coauthors = Pearson, Rick, and Garcia, Monique | date = 2007-08-16 | accessdate = 2007-09-27 | work = Chicago Tribune}}</ref>

On [[August 18]], [[2007]], Paul appeared in two notably favorable straw polls, conducted by the [[Strafford County, New Hampshire]], Republican Party, and by the West [[Alabama]] Republican Assembly. In New Hampshire, Paul received first place with 73% while his closest rival, Romney, received 9%.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.straffordcountyrepublicans.org/strafford/2007/08/18/strafford-county-republican-picnic-straw-poll-results/ | title = Strafford County Republican Picnic Straw Poll Results | publisher = Strafford County Republican Committee | date = 2007-08-18 | accessdate = 2007-09-27}}</ref> In Alabama the same day, Paul also placed first with 81%, and Romney took second again with 5%.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.usastrawpolls.com/states/Alabama-Straw-Polls.html | title = Alabama Straw Poll Results 2008 Presidential Election | last = Terr | first = David | date = 2007-08-18 | accessdate = 2007-09-27 | publisher = USA Election Polls}}</ref> On September 1, Paul placed third in the Texas Straw Poll, with 17% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/09/02/politics/main3228053.shtml | title = Duncan Hunter Wins Texas GOP Straw Poll | accessdate = 2007-09-28 | date = 2007-09-02 | publisher = CBS News}}</ref> Paul's overall head-to-head performance at [[Straw polling for the 2008 United States presidential election|Republican straw polls]] is comparable only to that of Romney or Thompson.<ref name="pollresults"/>

===Internet popularity===

Paul has participated in five [[Republican Presidential Debates, 2008|Republican presidential debates]], four of which he won according to the sponsors' own online or text-message phone polls. After the first debate, [[ABC News]] noted Paul's robust online presence: "His supporters have mastered the art of 'viral marketing,' using Internet savvy and blog postings to create at least the perception of momentum for his long-shot presidential bid."<ref>{{cite news | url = http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/Story?id=3147940 | title = ABC analysis of "The Ron Paul Effect"}}</ref> ''[[U.S. News]]'' reported his increasing online popularity: "His supporters have flocked to the Internet with such enthusiasm that Paul is now showing up among the much richer candidates in various measures of [[Internet traffic]]".<ref name="usnews0509"/> ''[[USA Today]]'' calls Paul an "online natural".<ref name=usatweb/>

Paul's Internet presence has been measured as a top Internet [[Search engine|search]] term by [[Technorati]],<ref name="usnews0509"/> [[Hitwise]],<ref name="hitwise"/> and [[Alexa Internet|Alexa]],<ref name="alexa"/> which rank popularity in the [[blogosphere]]. While some claim that Paul's high poll rankings are skewed by a small number of supporters who are intentionally inflating the statistics,<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,295969,00.html | title = You Decide: Results of "Hannity & Colmes" Text Messaging Poll | date = 2007-09-05 | accessdate = 2007-09-27 | coauthors = Hannity, Sean, and Colmes, Alan | work = Hannity & Colmes | publisher = Fox News}}</ref> Technorati spokesman Aaron Krane affirms his company's position that Paul's search popularity is genuine to the best of their knowledge.<ref name="usnews0509"/> On [[YouTube]], Paul holds first place among all presidential candidates, measured by total number of views.<ref name=youtube/> Paul also claims the most YouTube subscriptions of all candidates, having surpassed [[Barack Obama]] on [[May 20]], [[2007]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://ronpaul2008.typepad.com/ron_paul_2008/2007/05/paul_1_obama_2.html | title = Paul #1, Obama #2 | date = 2007-05-20 | accessdate = 2007-09-27 | publisher = Ron Paul 2008}}</ref> Paul's YouTube channel is one of the Top 40 most subscribed of all time, achieving 29,000 subscribers on [[September 27]], [[2007]].<ref name=ytc/>

==Political positions==

<!-- This section is a brief overview of Ron Paul's major political stances. Specifics should be added to [[Political positions of Ron Paul]]. -->

[[Image:Ronpaul1.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Paul at the 2007 National Right to Life Convention in [[Kansas City, MO]]; June 15, 2007.]]

{{main|Political positions of Ron Paul}}

Ron Paul's positions are developed from his long-standing promise that he "never votes for legislation unless the proposed measure is expressly authorized by the Constitution",<ref name="2008bio"/> which has yielded many contrarian votes and his "Dr. No" reputation. Paul supports [[free trade]], tighter border security, [[Right to bear arms|gun ownership]], a [[United States Constitution|Constitutional amendment]] allowing voluntary and unofficial [[school prayer]],<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ontheissues.org/2008/Ron_Paul_Education.htm#97-HJR78 | title = Ron Paul on Education: Supports a Constitutional Amendment for school prayer. | publisher = On the Issues}}</ref> [[Hard money (policy)|hard money]] such as the [[Silver standard|silver]] or [[gold standard]], and allowing workers to opt out of [[Social Security (United States)|Social Security]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://youtube.com/watch?v=jBvD4VVaGZI | title = Lee Rogers Interviews Ron Paul | last = Rogers | first = Lee | quote = 2:30–3:00}}</ref> He is also an advocate of [[Property|private property rights]] for [[pollution]] prevention,<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.dennismillerradio.com/pg/jsp/charts/audioMaster.jsp?dispid=301&headerDest=/pg/jsp/media/highlightswelcome.jsp | title = Dennis Miller interview | publisher = Dennis Miller Radio | accessdate = 2007-06-03}}</ref> ''[[habeas corpus]]'' for political detainees,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://andrewsullivan.theatlantic.com/the_daily_dish/2007/05/taking_ron_paul.html | title = Taking Ron Paul Seriously | accessdate = 2007-06-08 | last = Sullivan | first = Andrew | date = 2007-05-11}}</ref> and greater [[ballot access]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.house.gov/paul/congrec/congrec2004/cr071504.htm | title = End the Two-Party Monopoly! | publisher = House of Representatives | work = Congressional Record | accessdate = 2007-03-04}}</ref>

Paul calls himself "an unshakable foe of abortion"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ronpaul2008.com/issues/life-and-liberty/ | title = Life and Liberty | last = Paul | first = Ron | publisher = Ron Paul 2008 | accessdate = 2007-09-27}}</ref><ref>Paul says his years as an obstetrician lead him to believe life begins at conception.[http://www.teamliberty.net/id447.html] Paul's pro-life legislation, like the Sanctity of Life Act, is intended to negate ''Roe v. Wade'' for ethical reasons and because he wants to get "the federal government completely out of the business of regulating state matters."[http://www.lewrockwell.com/paul/paul301.html][http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Who+had+the+right+to+rule%3F+Accusations+about+the+abuses+of...-a0132162835 ]</ref> and believes regulation of medical decisions about maternal or fetal health is "best handled at the state level".<ref name="americanview"/> Paul also opposes federal regulation of "voluntary associations"<ref name="atgoogle">{{cite news | title = Candidates@Google: Ron Paul | publisher = Candidates at Google on YouTube | date = 2007-07-14 | url = http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yCM_wQy4YVg | accessdate = 2007-09-10 }}</ref> like marriages or civil unions, believing marriage is not a state function and should not require a government license.<ref name="sunsentinel">{{cite news | url = http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sfl-flbdebate0918nbsep18,0,2893863.story | title = GOP presidential debate in Fort Lauderdale focuses on conservative values | coauthors = Man, Anthony, and Ortega, Juan | date = 2007-07-18 | accessdate = 2007-09-27 | work = South Florida Sun-Sentinel}}</ref> Medically, he recognizes homosexuality is "too complex to give a [simple] answer."<ref name="americanview"/> He supports revising enforcement of the military "don't ask, don't tell" policy, which he calls "decent", to focus on behavior and include members with heterosexual as well as homosexual behavior issues.<ref name="atgoogle"/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0706/05/se.01.html | title = Transcript of [[June 5]] ''CNN/WMUR/New Hampshire Union Leader'' Republican presidential debate | accessdate = 2007-06-10 | date = 2007-06-05}}</ref>

Paul supports substantial reduction of the role of the federal government in the lives of individuals and in the functions of foreign and domestic [[state]]s. Paul is the only [[2008 Republican presidential candidates|2008 Republican presidential candidate]] to have voted against the [[Iraq Resolution|Iraq War Resolution]] in 2002.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.house.gov/paul/congrec/congrec2002/cr090402.htm | title = Arguments Against a War in Iraq | accessdate = 2007-07-07 | date = 2002-09-04 | last = Paul | first = Ron | publisher = House of Representatives | work = Congressional Record}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.house.gov/paul/congrec/congrec2002/cr100802.htm | title = Statement Opposing the use of Military Force against Iraq | accessdate = 2007-07-07 | last = Paul | first = Ron | date = 2002-09-08 | publisher = House of Representatives | work = Congressional Record}}</ref> Paul voted for the [[Authorization for Use of Military Force]] in response to the [[September 11, 2001 attacks|World Trade Center terror attacks]],<ref name="AUMF"/> but suggested war alternatives, including giving the president authority to grant [[Letters of Marque and Reprisal]] to target specific terrorists. Paul opposes illegal immigration, [[Birthright citizenship in the United States of America|birthright citizenship]], and [[amnesty]]. Paul also supports ending welfare benefits for illegal immigrants<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.lewrockwell.com/paul/paul269.html | title = Immigration and the Welfare State | last = Paul | first = Ron | publisher = Lew Rockwell}}</ref> and voted in favor of the [[Secure Fence Act of 2006]].

